##The way of dialysis under the invasion of epidemic situation

According to Wang Gang, a nephrologist at the hospital, there are 60 uremic patients in the district who receive hemodialysis 2-3 times a week. There are 4,719 dialysis patients in Wuhan, according to the Wuhan Dialysis Quality Control Centre. The dialysis centers at several hospitals have been closed due to the new pneumonia outbreak.

The full text is 3677 words and takes about 7.5 minutes to read

On the morning of January 30, Xiao Juan (not her real name) , 42, received a call back from the hotline of Wuhan's Mayor. According to the phone, she's ready for dialysis at the West Wing of Wuhan Union Hospital. The West Hospital of the Economic and Technological Development Zones was originally to be requisitioned as a designated hospital for fever, and all departments and outpatient clinics, including the hemodialysis center, were closed down, but there were so many dialysis patients in the hospital that the city decided that, the Dialysis Center at Concorde West Hospital continues to operate.

Xiao Juan is a uremic patient. Hemodialysis is one of the treatments she needs to survive. Before the outbreak of new crown pneumonia, she had been on dialysis for a long time in Hanyang Hospital district of Wuhan Chinese Medicine Hospital ("Chinese Medicine Hospital") . However, since January 27, the Chinese Medicine Hospital has been requisitioned as one of 24 hospitals for the treatment of fever patients, except for the fever out-patient clinic, clinics were closed, as were dialysis centers.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
January 28, was requisitioned for fixed-point Hospital, hospital of Traditional Chinese Medicine Dialysis Center empty. By Haiyang, Hsinking Daily News

After the hospital's dialysis center was closed, patients were either assigned to the headquarters of Wuhan's Hospital of Traditional Chinese medicine to continue their treatment, or actively seeking hospitals to accept them. As of the evening of January 28, all 60 dialysis patients in the hospital district had been found in the receiving hospital.

It's a life project, Wang Gang says.

━━━━━

Contact a dialysis center for 60 patients

At 10 a.m. on Jan. 26, Ding Ling, the head nurse of the Hemodialysis Center at the Chinese Medicine Hospital, issued a notice in his dialysis group that the dialysis center would be closed from the next day because the Chinese Medicine Hospital had been requisitioned as a designated treatment hospital for the third batch of patients with fever. "We checked a few dialysis rooms at hospitals that haven't been requisitioned, and they're all saturated, " Ding Ling said. "Let's see if we can get in touch. ".

Wang Gang, a nephrologist at the traditional Chinese Medicine Hospital, later apologized to patients in the group, asking them to understand the difficulty of the hospital: the Nephrology Department of the hospital will soon accept all new patients with coronary pneumonia.

Wang Gang and the doctors received the news early on the 26th, when the Wuhan Municipal Health and Health Commission said in a notice that TCM hospitals would be requisitioned to be designated hospitals for fever.

As of 2400 hours on January 30,2020,2,639 new cases of pneumonia and 159 deaths had been reported in Wuhan, according to the Health Commission of Hubei Province. In response to the outbreak, Wuhan has decided to requisition 24 general hospitals in batches and temporarily convert them into designated hospitals for fever patients, bringing the total number of beds to about 10,000.

At the time of the call, doctors in Hanyang District's nephrology department were scrambling to connect 60 of their patients with dialysis centers at hospitals. They have found Wuhan Yaxin General Hospital, Hanyang Hospital, the city center hospital, the city first hospital, but the hospital hemodialysis center said there are no spare beds. As a result of co-ordination, 22 patients were transferred to the Wuhan Chinese Medicine Hospital headquarters in Hankou for further treatment.

As for the other 38 patients, the doctors thought of private medical institutions. In the end, Tongji University agreed to admit seven patients and a privately run dialysis center admitted 14.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On the evening of January 28, patients gathered in the outpatient hall of a traditional Chinese Medicine Hospital hoping that the hospital would help arrange new dialysis facilities. By Haiyang, Hsinking Daily News

In Wang Gang's view, dialysis is a life project, and patients who don't get it die. "We have a long history with patients and we all feel sorry for you. "

At the other end of the wechat group, patients are also looking for a way out.

On January 26,13 patients found their own dialysis centres in places such as Hanyang hospital through their own channels. The mayor of 12345 was also called to ask the government for help in closing the dialysis center, and the operator said she would keep a record of everyone's questions and let patients wait for news.

By 10 p.m. , 56 patients had found dialysis slots, and only four had yet to be admitted.

The "positive" patients received one-on-one treatment

Xiao Juan (not her real name) is one of the four missing and also a "positive" patient.

A "positive" patient is a dialysis patient with a blood-borne disease, such as hepatitis. According to the former Ministry of Health issued in 2010, "management norms for hemodialysis rooms in medical institutions, " "positive" patients need to undergo special hemodialysis in isolated environments, quarantined areas and hemodialysis machines should not be used in conjunction with patients suffering from other infectious diseases.

In patient circles, dialysis machines for "positive" patients are called "positive beds" and are few in number. The Chinese Medicine Hospital, for example, has 17 beds in its dialysis center, of which only four are positive.

After the closure of the hospital, Xiao contacted the dialysis center of the Tongji Medical College, which is affiliated to the Tongji Hospital. The other side said that the dialysis patients from the affiliated hospital had been transferred to the department for Dialysis and the beds were full. She contacted the Wuhan Union Hospital, Asin General, and Hanyang Hospital, and got the same answer: No beds.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
One patient rolled up her sleeves and had a persistent dialysis puff on her arm. By Haiyang, Hsinking Daily News

On January 28, Xiao Juan had not been on dialysis for four days. She had cut back on her water intake since the night before.

That afternoon, she arrived at Hanyang Hospital without an appointment.

Under the guidance of a doctor, Xiao Juan came to the door of hemodialysis department. Nearby service window nurse heard that Xiao Juan is not a patient of this hospital, also did not have an appointment, told her hemodialysis department has been saturated, can only receive in advance appointment patients. In recent days, the dialysis unit has received more than 20 patients transferred from other hospitals, nurses said, and health care workers have shifted from double to triple shifts, working 12-hour days.

That afternoon, Xiao Juan still couldn't get dialysis.

That night, Xiao Juan and several other patients back to the hospital of traditional Chinese medicine, hope to help re-arrangement. Chinese Medicine Hospital quickly with a number of hospitals docking, coordination, she was assigned to the Puai Hospital Gutian district dialysis. At 8:30 pm on January 29th, Xiao Juan finished her dialysis. Because is "positive" patient, the Universal Love Hospital opened a night shift specially for her, one-on-one treatment.

The clinic was closed to avoid cross-contamination

In the lobby of the Chinese Medicine Hospital, Wang Gang, a nephrologist who wears a blue surgical mask over a 3m mask, has been contacting dialysis beds for patients for the past few days. Wang Gang said one of the main reasons hospitals are closing their dialysis centers is that they have been requisitioned to be hospitals with fever.

After being requisitioned, Chinese Medicine hospitals will be divided into clean areas, contaminated areas, clean areas are the rest and living areas of medical staff, contaminated areas are the areas where suspicious patients are isolated and hospitalized. Dialysis centers are located in the middle of the clean and contaminated areas and are prone to cross-contamination. "Dialysis patients have poor health, high blood pressure, malnutrition and so on, and the risk of infection is much higher, " Wang Gang said in a husky voice.

A staff member of the Medical Department of the Chinese Medicine Hospital also said that once the dialysis center is opened, it will be difficult to prevent cross-infection of new coronavirus in dialysis patients. "If you have a non-pneumonia patient in the hospital who has a new coronavirus, we have too much responsibility. "

However, not all fever hospitals have closed their dialysis centers. According to incomplete statistics from Hsinking, among the 24 designated hospitals, the city's Fifth Hospital, Puai Hospital Gutian Hospital district, the city's Third Hospital Guanggu Hospital district did not close the Hemodialysis Center; The haemodialysis centers of seven hospitals, including the Houhu district of the Central Hospital, the City Red Cross hospital, and the Zhongfa Xincheng district of Tongji Hospital, have been closed.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On January 28, the fourth floor of the Chinese Medicine Hospital's Dialysis Center was evacuated. By Haiyang, Hsinking Daily News

In response, Liu Tao, deputy director of the Nephrology Department of the Chinese Medicine Hospital, said, "New crown pneumonia is a droplet-borne infection that can affect anyone. Therefore, whether the dialysis center is closed or not depends on whether the dialysis room and the fever clinic are connected together and in the same building.the reason why the city's fifth hospital is able to keep the dialysis center, because it's outside the clinic, patients are less likely to cross-infect.

At the TCM hospital, the dialysis center is located in the middle of the fourth floor clinic building, the emergency department in the south, and the medical staff's office in the north. "dialysis rooms like ours are hard to separate from fever clinics, so they have to be closed. "

Cross-hospital settlement of dialysis fee

The problem of post-transfer costs is another.

According to a patient, according to the relevant national regulations, out-patients with serious chronic diseases can choose a designated medical insurance hospital for treatment and reimbursement, dialysis patients reimbursement rate of about 87% . But if not in the selected designated hospital dialysis, the cost can not be reimbursed. The patient said that if he paid for himself, the cost would be about 700 yuan each time, more than 2,000 yuan three times a week, or more than 8,000 yuan a month, "My family is well-off and can afford it for a month or two, but what if it takes longer? Not to mention that many dialysis patients are low-income families. "

In contrast to traditional Chinese Medicine hospitals, some of the dialysis centers that have been requisitioned for fever-targeted hospitals have arranged for patients to be transferred earlier.

Like uremia patient Wang Yong. Previously, the city's Red Cross hospital was Wang Yong's designated hospital for the treatment of serious chronic diseases. Before the New Year, the hospital informed Wang Yong that it was being requisitioned. Wang Yong quickly contacted the dialysis center in the Back Lake District of the downtown hospital, using it as a new dialysis center, and the social security relationship was turned around.

Later, the Houhuyuan district was also requisitioned, and Wang Yong was transferred to the City Center Hospital, the Nanjing Road Hospital district, for dialysis. However, since the Houhu Hospital district and Nanjing Road Hospital district belong to the city center hospital, so reimbursement is not a problem.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On the evening of January 26, doctors in the Nephrology Department of a traditional Chinese Medicine Hospital finally found a way out for 56 patients after a hard day's work. By Haiyang, Hsinking Daily News

"In a case like Wang Yong's, maybe the Red Cross Hospital in the city got the news earlier, so it has time to make arrangements, " said Liu Tao, but the Chinese Medicine Hospital only received the notice to close the clinic and the Dialysis Center on January 26, it goes into effect January 27th. This time is too hasty, it is difficult for patients to plan a way out.

But the TCM hospital has also come up with some solutions, such as negotiating with Poh and deciding to waive patients'dialysis fees at Poh first, which will then be settled by the TCM hospital and Poh.

On the other hand, as dialysis centres in Wuhan hospitals have been closed, the ones that are still operating are overloaded.

According to the patient, at present, the Hemodialysis Center in Nanjing Road Hospital District of the city center hospital is already in a "24-hour-on-the-clock" state. The medical staff are on four shifts, day and night are "8 to 12,1 to 5. ".

On Jan. 29, staff at the Dialysis Center of Nanjing Road Hospital in the city center declined an interview with the Beijing News, but said they had accepted more than 200 dialysis patients from Houhu Hospital, and the total number of dialysis patients is now more than 500.

In response to the situation, a Wuhan Hospital Hemodialysis Center head Nurse said that although overworked, but will still provide treatment for patients, because every patient has the right to survive.
